{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487230"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"286"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/286"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.04,0.09,0.7,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92550"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/286"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1284"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92550"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents for review of his Parkinson\u0027s disease. He was diagnosed six years ago on the basis of a resting tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia primarily affecting his upper limbs. He has been taking levodopa with carbidopa three times a day at near maximal dose. He now presents with worsened Parkinson\u0027s symptoms in the one-two hours prior to each dose.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase levodopa dose and reduce frequency","Change to prochlorperazine","Change levodopa to rotigotine patch","Change to controlled release levodopa","Ablative surgery"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a wearing-off effect. This is indicated by the worsening of Parkinsonian symptoms shortly before each dose of levodopa is taken.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of wearing-off effect includes \u003Cstrong\u003Echanging to a controlled release formulation of levodopa/carbidopa\u003C/strong\u003E. Other possible therapies include addition of a COMT inhibitor, which prevents metabolic breakdown of dopamine and improves the transportation of levodopa across the blood brain barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotigotine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a non-ergot-derived dopamine agonist and is used as an adjunct to levodopa so would not be appropriate to replace levodopa completely in this situation. As a patch formulation, it is helpful for patients who have difficulty swallowing, impaired gastric emptying or prefer the once-daily dose. Patients need to be warned however of the potential side effects of sleep attacks and compulsive behaviours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProchlorperazine \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be helpful as it can exacerbate Parkinson\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAblative therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be of benefit in advanced Parkinson\u0027s symptoms but when pharmaceutical options have been optimised which is not in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom a practical standpoint the oral bioavailability of CR levodopa formulations is less, so the total dose may need to be increased and that due to a slower onset time the first dose of the day often still needs to be immediate release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther effective options include addition of a dopamine agonist, selective MAO-B inhibitor or use of a portable intraduodenal pump for levodopa/carbidopa administration.\u00a0Another legitimate option would be further fractionating the dose by i\u003Cstrong\u003Encreasing the frequency\u003C/strong\u003E, with or without reducing the dose (not increasing the dose with decreased frequency).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Controlled release levodopa can be effective treatment for wearing-off effects."],"references":["Simon R, Aminoff M, Greenberg D, Clinical Neurology 10th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill 2018"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"286"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T10:57:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T10:57:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"286"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"